## Reading Real CSS

The basics — selectors, properties, values, the box model, layout — cover most of what you will encounter. But real-world CSS has a few additional patterns that show up constantly. None of them are hard to read once you know what to look for.

### Media queries: CSS that adapts to screen size

```css
@media (max-width: 768px) {
  .nav {
    flex-direction: column;
  }
}
```

> "When the screen is 768 pixels wide or smaller, change the navigation from a row to a column."

Media queries are CSS instructions that only activate under certain conditions — usually screen size. They are how websites become "responsive" (work on both desktop and mobile).

The pattern is always the same:

```css
@media (condition) {
  /* CSS rules that only apply when the condition is true */
}
```

Common breakpoints you will see:
- `max-width: 768px` — tablets and smaller
- `max-width: 480px` — phones
- `min-width: 1024px` — desktop and larger

When a layout looks fine on desktop but breaks on mobile, the media queries are where you look.

### Hover states: CSS that responds to the mouse

```css
.button:hover {
  background-color: darkblue;
}
```

> "When the user hovers their mouse over a `.button`, change the background to dark blue."

The `:hover` pseudo-class is added after a selector to define what happens when you hover over that element. You will also see:

- `:focus` — when an element is selected (like clicking into an input field)
- `:active` — the brief moment when you are clicking/pressing an element
- `:first-child`, `:last-child` — targets the first or last element in a group

These always follow the pattern `selector:state`.

### Transitions: smooth changes

```css
.button {
  background-color: blue;
  transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
}

.button:hover {
  background-color: darkblue;
}
```

> "The button is blue. When hovered, it changes to dark blue. The `transition` makes that change happen smoothly over 0.3 seconds instead of instantly."

Without `transition`, changes happen instantly (one frame it is blue, the next it is dark blue). With `transition`, the browser smoothly animates between the two states.

The pattern: `transition: [what to animate] [how long] [easing];`

### CSS variables: reusable values

```css
:root {
  --primary-color: #3b82f6;
  --spacing: 16px;
}

.button {
  background-color: var(--primary-color);
  padding: var(--spacing);
}
```

> "Define a primary color and spacing value once, then use them anywhere with `var()`."

CSS variables (custom properties) start with `--` and are used with `var()`. They let you change a color or spacing value in one place and have it update everywhere. If a client says "change the brand color," you only need to update the variable, not every rule that uses that color.

When you see `var(--something)` in CSS, it is referencing a variable defined somewhere else — usually at the top of the stylesheet in `:root`.

### The strategy for unknown properties

You will encounter CSS properties you do not recognize. That is completely normal — there are hundreds of them. Here is your strategy:

1. **Read the property name.** CSS properties are usually descriptive: `border-radius` rounds corners, `text-transform` changes capitalization, `box-shadow` adds a shadow.
2. **Read the value.** Values often give context: `uppercase`, `none`, `hidden`, `auto`.
3. **If still unclear, search for it.** Searching "CSS [property-name]" gives you an answer in seconds.

Do not try to memorize CSS properties. The ones you encounter frequently will become familiar. For the rest, knowing how to look them up is the skill.

